A 'Crotalus pyrrhus' is a species of venomous pit viper found in Mexico and southern USA. 
It has a distinctive rust-red or brownish color with dark-centered dorsal scales.
Its skin has a rough, scaly texture with diamond-shaped patterns.
The head of the 'Crotalus pyrrhus' is triangular in shape and relatively large compared to its body.
It can grow up to 4 feet in length and has a stout, cylindrical body.
The 'Crotalus pyrrhus' is known for its highly toxic venom, which it delivers through its long, hinged fangs.
It can be found in a variety of habitats, including deserts, rocky outcrops, grasslands, and forests.
